Strong priorities for fragile states
LONDON/MONROVIA/KIGALI – No country has been spared the fallout of COVID-19.
However, the most "fragile" states in the world are facing a particularly complex set of challenges.
In fact, before the pandemic began, Yemen, Sudan, Haiti, Sierra Leone, Myanmar, Afghanistan, Venezuela, and other countries were already struggling with poverty, conflict, corruption, and weak public administration.
Today, these factors leave these countries ill-equipped to manage the COVID-19 crisis.
What every country needs to get through the pandemic is precisely what the fragile states lack: a state apparatus capable of developing and implementing an action plan, an effective police force to enforce the rules, social programs that provide funds, supplies, and health services to care for infected individuals.
The lack of state capacity is immediately felt in the public health sector.
While Europe has 4,000 intensive care beds per million inhabitants, several African regions have only five per million inhabitants.
Mali has only three ventilators for the entire country.
An effective response also requires trust in the state's intervention.
However, in addition to its lack of resources, the public administration of most fragile states does not benefit much from the population's support.
In countries recovering from conflict or suffering from endemic corruption, many people will hesitate to support the government even if it proves capable of governing.
A strong private sector is also an essential component of effective and resilient states.
Citizens should be able to work to support their families, and the state should be able to collect tax revenues to help those who cannot do so.
However, in fragile states, the formal economy is not sufficiently present to meet these needs.
Earlier during the crisis, there was hope that some fragile states would avoid the worst health consequences of COVID-19 due to the demographic weight of youth and geographic distance.
However, from our perspective as co-chairs of the new Council on State Fragility, we must admit that this was not the case.
In the past few weeks, Sudan, South Sudan, Somalia, and Yemen have all had infection and mortality rates rivaling those of developed countries that were first hit by the coronavirus.
Worse still, the economic consequences of the pandemic will certainly be more severe for fragile states. These will not only result from national lockdowns, but also from what is happening abroad.
Trade with countries like China has declined, remittances from expatriates have dropped, prices of basic goods and oil revenues have collapsed, and deficits are accumulating.
Since fragile states rely on imports for most of their food supply, there is increasingly talk of "hunger" and even "famine."
We should now have realized that the problems of less developed countries are becoming mostly global problems, whether in the form of mass migration, criminal or terrorist organizations, or economic repercussions.
Given that half of the destitute populations will live in fragile states by 2030, these problems will only continue to worsen.
This is why the Council on State Fragility has made it an absolute priority to draw attention to the specific challenges these countries must face.
The council, composed of former global leaders, ministers, diplomats, business figures, academics, and heads of development organizations, will combine cutting-edge research with meticulous political knowledge. Its aim will be to guide national and international policymakers on how fragile states will emerge from this crisis and how they will tackle their broader and deeper problems.
Decentralization, adaptability, and the prudent use of data will be essential.
For example, it has been widely proven that "targeted lockdowns" of local outbreaks are often more appropriate than national lockdowns.
Such knowledge could prove crucial for fragile states.
Nevertheless, we must act quickly before the critical phase of the pandemic in the West comes to an end and the sense of urgency dissipates.
We propose five recommendations.
Firstly, access to social protection should be simpler and faster.
Sometimes, this will mean universal eligibility rather than precise targeting.
Mobile telephone networks should be used to gather information on immediate needs and to disburse small regular payments (although of limited duration).
Secondly, national food production should be encouraged.
For example, Sierra Leone, which used to grow rice, has become increasingly dependent in recent decades.
More generally, Africa accounts for 60% of the world's unused arable land.
Initiatives for local production of basic crops must be rapidly deployed on a significantly larger scale.
Thirdly, once vaccine production begins, the international community must ensure that fragile states are not excluded from the market by wealthier countries.
When the threat is a contagious pathogen, no country is safe unless all are.
We must advocate for and accelerate the production of multiple vaccines to ensure rapid and widespread distribution.
Fourthly, businesses in fragile states need immediate assistance.
As noted by the most involved international development institutions; small businesses in less affluent countries are often neglected and suffer the adverse consequences of broader goals and rules (since it is easier to achieve a goal by investing in large-scale projects in larger economies).
However, it is precisely these small businesses that need more significant investments.
Finally, the G20 should do more to support heavily indebted fragile states that are forced to choose between paying their foreign creditors or saving their population.
It is expected that countries receiving bilateral development aid will repay approximately $40 billion to private and public creditors this year alone.
To prevent this financial shock, we urge all G20 members to suspend accumulated debts not only until next year, but also until the end of the crisis.
Furthermore, it is crucial that all fragile states receive emergency financing to support their efforts to contain COVID-19 and mitigate its economic repercussions — particularly countries that do not usually have access to World Bank or International Monetary Fund financing.
COVID-19 will exacerbate existing problems in all fragile states around the world.
However, if the international community responds quickly, we can mitigate the worst effects of the pandemic.
If there is one lesson to be learned from this crisis, it is that livelihoods and lives will be saved if we act faster than the virus.
